    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal balance is a common sight in the student loan realm, much like a stubborn old gnome who refuses to budge from his favorite spot. It's because you're paying off the interest first, and only the remaining amount goes toward the principal. It's like trying to move a boulder with a feather; the interest is the feather, and the principal is the boulder. As you continue to make the same monthly payment, the interest portion decreases, but the principal portion remains small, so the balance decreases slowly. It's a bit like trying to fill a leaky bucket while the water keeps dripping out. Keep at it, though, and eventually, you'll see the principal balance start to decrease more noticeably. Just remember, patience is a virtue, even for a goblin.",
